Author: .deche
Content: Hi I'm learning to use starknet-py. In this code, how to get the value 340282366920938463463374607431768211583? Is that the equivalent to call data [127, 1] ?

Author: trejowsk
Content: In that example the transformation is performed based on your contract's arguments types. Type of `amount` here is `UInt256` which will be translated to array of 2 felts in calldata equivalent, since this structure consists of 2 consecutive felts (low and high felt values). You can also pass a dict if it makes things easier for you (should consist of `{"low": 127, "high": 1} `).  We provide the possibility to pass a simple python integer in the  `UInt256` range for `UInt256` arguments for user's ease of use, and we decode it later to corresponding calldata to be cairo-compatible.

Author: trejowsk
Content:
I think you probably mean ERC20 tokens. Given a deployed OpenZeppelin ERC20 Contract on Starknet, one can retrieve the contract with our contract class (docs: https://starknetpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/quickstart.html#using-contract), and invoke the transfer function with proper arguments. Cairo implementation for ERC20 from OpenZeppelin can be found here:
https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/contracts/token/ERC20.cairo. ERC20 implementation may vary though, so you might want to check which one you are using for that token

Author: mandarkest
Content:
Hey team, 2 questions:
1) How can I reuse AccountClient in different sessions?
2) I want to send a transaction via AccountClient to a contract which is not deployed via AccountClient. Is there a straightforward way to do this?

Author: Przemek#4299
Content:
Hi @Prince | JediSwap 
1) It is not well documented yet (we'll add it right now!), but you can create AccountClient object without deploying new contract by using its constructor instead of create_account method.
Example snippet how to do it:
```
from starknet_py.net import AccountClient, KeyPair
AccountClient(YOUR_ACCOUNT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS, KeyPair.from_private_key(YOUR_ACCOUNT_CONTRACT_PRIVATE_KEY), "testnet")
```
We pass KeyPair object create using your private key. You can retrive account_address and private_key from the AccountClient object when you created it for the first time. Also you can change "testnet" to any URL you want.
2) Yes, you can do it. You can use add_transaction method of AccountClient. Called contract does not have to be deployed via same account. 

Btw, we recommend using Contract object (again, create it via constructor without deploying extra contract) and making you calls through that object

Author: _sam___
Content: @Prince | JediSwap i have a code example here of what i think you're looking for: https://hackmd.io/@sambarnes/By7kitOCt#Accounts-with-Starknetpy

Author: _sam___
Content:
First create the StarkNet client, along with an AccountClient loaded from the account's contract address
```
from starknet_py.contract import Contract
from starknet_py.net.client import Client
from starknet_py.net.account.account_client import AccountClient, KeyPair
from starkware.python.utils import from_bytes

network = "http://localhost:5000"
chain_id = from_bytes(b"SN_LOCALHOST")
starknet_client = Client(net=network, chain=chain_id)
account_client = AccountClient(
    address=config.signer_address,  # a string, 0x...
    key_pair=KeyPair.from_private_key(config.signer_secret),  # an integer private key
    net=network,
    chain=chain_id,
)
```

Then later on you can use that account client in your contract constructor:
```
    contract = await Contract.from_address(
        address=config.contract_address,
        client=account_client,
    )
```
Then use contract as you would before, sigs created automatically, and call will be proxied through the account contract before hitting the actual contract

Author: mandarkest
Content:
Hey. Contract.from_address doesn't work correctly for proxy contracts as abi fetched is incorrect. 

for ex: This is the starknet ETH contract. https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x049d36570d4e46f48e99674bd3fcc84644ddd6b96f7c741b1562b82f9e004dc7

I get error when calling below:
```
token = await Contract.from_address(token_1_address, current_client)
result = await token.functions["decimals"].call()
```

```
KeyError: 'decimals'
```

Author: cptartur
Content: Are you sure you contract has `decimals` method? From what I see on voyager, there's no suche method.

Author: mandarkest
Content: Yep. The implementation has decimals method. Proxy contract doesn’t. It redirects using default. When I initiate the contract using explicit abi, it works fine.

Author: cptartur
Content: `Contract.from_address` builds contract definition from what is returned by starknet feeder gateway `get_code` call. If proxy has no explicit definition of `decimals`, starknet.py won't be aware of it's exsistence.

Author: cptartur
Content: You can see https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/get_code?contractAddress=0x049d36570d4e46f48e99674bd3fcc84644ddd6b96f7c741b1562b82f9e004dc7

Author: mandarkest
Content: So get_code should be changed then?

Author: mandarkest
Content:
https://starknet.io/docs/hello_starknet/default_entrypoint.html
https://medium.com/starkware/starknet-alpha-0-7-0-26e04db03509

Author: cptartur
Content: Unfortunately this is beyond starknet.py, as gateway is part of starknet itself

Author: mandarkest
Content:
I believe this should be handled by starknet.py. As you can see this for the implementation address:

https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/get_code?contractAddress=0x4bb0f7af15a5469be4a571c8660d9aaf39e7e67f27f774702d75e77141ef90

Author: mandarkest
Content: So, when starknet.py detects an implementation in abi, call that, and get code from there.

Author: mandarkest
Content: @guthl | StarkWare What is your opinion on above? Should this scenario handled at gateway level or at starknet.py level?

Author: JakubPtak#8889
Content:
There are many ways to implement a proxy and there could be a chain of proxies and even a circular dependency between them. 
In production usage you should provide your ABI explicitly, `from_address` is a helper for playing with the lib.

Author: mandarkest
Content: Ok, that does make sense. I will switch all my calls to explicit definitions then. Thanks both of you !

Author: JakubPtak#8889
Content: I think we had a warning to avoid using `from_address` in production code, but there is something wrong with the docs atm 😱 . We'll fix docs and make sure it is stated explicitly. Thank you for bringing this into our attention 🙏

Author: cheechyuan.eth

Author: trejowsk
Content: I actually think that the signature verification algorithm can be different across accounts - that is the core characteristic of the account abstraction. The implementations can and will differ across the board, and that’s the current state, OpenZeppelin and ArgentX are different and that’s why starknet.py cannot handle all of them at once, AccountClient conforms to signing metod of OZ’s account. I believe there is (or will be) a Signer interface which will allow you to replace the signing Logic with your own (see API reference of account client)

Author: cptartur
Content: Signer interface already exists in the current release and can be used to create w custom signer that will work with different signing schema than we're using by default in AccountClient. One thing I've realized though, signer is not very well documented - this is going to get fixed.

Author: janek26
Content:
Hey, argent x wallets sign the same way open zeppelin accounts sign. There was a change how they sign post v0.1.0 of the openzeppelin contract, which is already in openzeppelin develop branch. You should use the latest contract from that branch instead of the tagged release
Maybe we can get v0.2.0 of the openzeppelin contracts soon

Author: cecco_
Content: How do I decode event's data from a list of felts? provided that I have the abi of course.

Author: war_in
Content:
Hi, you can use DataTransformer. Here is an example of how to create and use it:

`data_transformer=DataTransformer(abi=events_abi,`
`identifier_manager=identifier_manager_from_abi(abi))`
`transformed_data = data_transformer.to_python(data)`

* abi is the abi of the contract
* events_abi is the abi of an event you want to decode, for example:

`{'data': [{'name': 'new_governor_nominee', 'type': 'felt'}, {'name': 'nominated_by', 'type': 'felt'}], 'keys': [], 'name': 'governor_nominated', 'type': 'event'}`

However, there is a problem with the event’s abi. It has ‘data’ instead of ‘outputs’ and we currently don’t support that. I’ve created an issue (https://github.com/software-mansion/starknet.py/issues/231) on our github, but it can take some time to finish it, so there is a workaround.

You can take the event’s abi and change the ‘data’ key to ‘outputs’.

events_abi["outputs"] = events_abi.pop("data")

Content: Support for 0.9.1 is in the works and we're hoping for a release tomorrow. Until that this and other things may be broken

Author: cptartur
Content: Hey, you've identified correctly this is a limitation of namedtuples. I know it's possible for namedtuples to automatically rename invalid fields but this is perhaps not ideal. We'll investigate if more elegant solution is possible without making major changes to how `DataTransformer` works.

Author: 0xca11ab1e
Content: Actually, using `rename=True` would be just great. It's a tiny change. I could open a PR if you are OK with that.

Author: 0xca11ab1e
Content: No, the renaming would be incorrect. But we could go with a "slotted" frozen dataclass.

Author: cptartur
Content: Hey, could you elaborate what you mean with `"slotted" frozen dataclass`?

Author: 0xca11ab1e
Content:
Something like that (not tested):```python
from dataclasses import make_dataclass

# instead of the namedtuple:
result = make_dataclass("Result", [(k, v) for k, v in ...], order=True, frozen=True, slots=True)
```
cf https://docs.python.org/3/library/dataclasses.html#dataclasses.make_dataclass

Author: 0xca11ab1e
Content: But then, I'm not sure if we will keep the capability to do a tuple comparison (like `result == (0, 1)`), which is a mandatory requirement IMO.

Author: cptartur
Content: We'll look into that. Though it seems like `slots` parameter was added in 3.10 and we need to support >=3.7

Author: rarub
Content: Hi! I'm currently working on deploying a proxy with starknet.py. I get a `KeyError` because the ABI of the Proxy doesn't include the functions of the implementation contract. I saw a question here earlier that said you have to switch to explicit definitions. Could someone provide an example of how to do that?

Author: war_in
Content:
Hi, here is an example:
- deploy a proxy with Contract.deploy:

`proxy_deployment = await Contract.deploy(
        compiled_contract=compiled_proxy,
        constructor_args=[class_hash],
        client=client,
    )
`
class_hash is a hash of the class you want have proxy to

- wait for acceptance

`await proxy_deployment.wait_for_acceptance()
proxy = proxy_deployment.deployed_contract
`
- create an instance of proxy with different abi

`proxy = Contract(address=proxy.address, abi=abi, client=client)
`
abi is an abi of the contract you want have proxy to

And that's all. Let me know if that helped!

Content: Hey, with starknet.py 0.4.0 we've introduced custom dataclasses for client responses so we have mostly uniform results for both gateway and rpc client as rpc will become the default way of interacting with starknet at some point in the future. Since rpc receipt has currently no concept of `execution_resources`, we've removed it from the response. Is this removal a big problem for you?

There's no parameter `blocknumber` in `get_block`. It should be `block_number` instead. Author: JakubPtak#8889
Content:
So I guess `test` is an address written as a hex with `0x` at the beginning, like `0xad23132...bda12`? You need to turn it into an int first, python ints support arbitrary range, so we don't need to string type those things. We allow passing short strings that are translated like strings in cairo - every character gets encoded.

If value is constant, then you can do `test = 0xad23132bda12` and python will read it as an int right away. 
If you don't know this value statically you can use `int(your_hex, 16)`

Content:
If you mean translating short strings then we offer `decode_shortstring in starknet_py.cairo.felt`. We don't have any function to create a long string from an array of felts.

Author: war_in
Content:
Hey #🐍｜starknet-py  StarkNet is preparing for a huge change! In a week from now, the loved `Deploy` transaction will be gone 😢  It means that the old deployment flow will be broken!
But don’t worry, we are already ready 🔥 StarkNet.py 0.10.0 introduced some useful features (`Deployer`, `Contract.declare` and `Contract.deploy_contract`). You can read about them in the `Deploying contracts` section in our docs! 
https://starknetpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guide.html#deploying-contracts

Here is a list of features we are going to remove next week!
- Contract.deploy
- AccountClient.create_account
- Client.deploy
- make_deploy_tx
- compute_deploy_hash
- `Deploy` transaction

Author: wrong_man
Content:
my code is really 99% copy paste from the link i mentioned above:
```python
from starknet_py.net import KeyPair
from starknet_py.net.account.account import Account
from starknet_py.net.gateway_client import GatewayClient
from starknet_py.net.models import StarknetChainId, compute_address


# First, make sure to generate private key and salt
class_hash_opz=0x06f500f527355dfdb8093c7fe46e6f73c96a867392b49fa4157a757538928539
key_pair = KeyPair.from_private_key("my_seed")
salt=KeyPair.from_private_key("my other seed")
network="testnet"

# Compute an address
address = compute_address(
    salt=salt.public_key,
    class_hash=class_hash_opz,  # class_hash of the Account declared on the StarkNet
    constructor_calldata=[key_pair.public_key],
    deployer_address=0,
)
# Prefund the address (using the token bridge or by sending fee tokens to the computed address)
# Make sure the tx has been accepted on L2 before proceeding

# Create an Account instance
account = Account(
    address=address,
    client=GatewayClient(net=network),
    key_pair=key_pair,
    chain=StarknetChainId.TESTNET,
)



async def sign_dep_acc():
    deploy_account_tx = await account.sign_deploy_account_transaction(
        class_hash=class_hash_opz,
        contract_address_salt=salt.public_key,
        constructor_calldata=[key_pair.public_key],
        max_fee=int(1e15),
    )
    return deploy_account_tx

import asyncio
deploy_account_signed=asyncio.run(sign_dep_acc())

async def deploy_account(deploy_account_tx):
    resp = await account.client.deploy_account(transaction=deploy_account_tx)
    return resp
resp= asyncio.run(deploy_account(deploy_account_signed))
async def get_tx_status(tx):
    status = await account.client.wait_for_tx(tx)
    return status

status=asyncio.run(get_tx_status(resp.transaction_hash))
```

Author: seven#1150
Content:
My code is as follows:
`import asyncio

from starknet_py.net.account.account import Account
from starknet_py.net.gateway_client import GatewayClient
from starknet_py.net.models import StarknetChainId, compute_address
from starknet_py.net.networks import TESTNET
from starknet_py.net.signer.stark_curve_signer import KeyPair

# First, make sure to generate private key and salt
from starkware.starknet.testing.starknet import Starknet

private_key = 0x12345
key_pair = KeyPair. from_private_key(private_key)
salt = KeyPair.from_private_key(private_key).public_key
class_hash = 0x025ec026985a3bf9d0cc1fe17326b245dfdc3ff89b8fde106542a3ea56c5a918
# Compute an address
address = compute_address(
     salt=salt,
     class_hash=class_hash, # class_hash of the Account declared on the Starknet
     constructor_calldata=[key_pair. public_key],
     deployer_address=0,
)
print(f'address:{address}-{hex(address)}')

# Prefund the address (using the token bridge or by sending fee tokens to the computed address)
# Make sure the tx has been accepted on L2 before proceeding

# Define the client to be used to interact with Starknet
client = GatewayClient(net=TESTNET)
chain = StarknetChainId.TESTNET

async def main():
     # Use `Account.deploy_account` static method to deploy an account
     account_deployment_result = await Account.deploy_account(
         address=address,
         class_hash=class_hash,
         salt=salt,
         key_pair=key_pair,
         client=client,
         chain=chain,
         constructor_calldata=[key_pair. public_key],
         max_fee=int(1e16),
     )
     # Wait for deployment transaction to be accepted
     await account_deployment_result.wait_for_acceptance()

     # From now on, account can be used as usual
     account = account_deployment_result.account

asyncio. run(main())`

Author: drerfy
Content:
Hi guys! Back to starknet-py again. There were questions about the starting guide https://starknetpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/account_creation.html . 
What restrictions are present in starknet for the value of "private_key"? Could it be ethereum private key? Are there restrictions on the value of the "salt" field? (Except that it shouldn't be 0, of course) Where do I get the "class_hash" value from?

Author: cptartur
Content:
`class_hash` is an identifier of an account contract declared on Starknet. It will depend on what account contract you will decide to use to create your account. You can read more about accounts in starknet here
https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/Account_Abstraction/introduction/

Author: cptartur
Content: What can be used for `private_key` depends on the account contract. Salt should be a securely generated value - we do not provide any methods for that in the starknet.py itself.

Author: saniksin
Content:
Use the starknet.js library; the starknet.py library is heavy on functions under the hood. Alternatively, you can implement your own signing logic. The issue lies in the signature array elements: during deployment, both openzeppelin and argent utilize a signature array with two elements (r and s).

However, the deployment array for braavos consists of 10 elements, and starknet.py doesn't support this signature type. (array r, s, braavosclasshash, and [0] * 7)

Content: I'm trying to upgrade my (wallet) account using starknet.py instead of Argent wallet UI. does anyone know how to do this? I tried to invoke the "upgrade" function of the account's "contract" but that doesn't seem to be working. Is there a different way to access the functions of a wallet account contract?

Author: matthewchen
Content:
"`
  call_upgrade = Call(
      to_addr=account.address,
      selector=get_selector_from_name("upgrade"),
      calldata=[0x1a736d6ed154502257f02b1ccdf4d9d1089f80811cd6acad48e6b6a9d1f2003, 0x0],
  )
  calls = [call_upgrade]
  response = await account.execute(calls=calls, max_fee=MAX_FEE)
"`

Author: lagnisiruk
Content: Thank you so much! That worked like a charm

Author: matthewchen
Content:

from starknet_py.hash.casm_class_hash import compute_casm_class_hash
